{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fb383696-1e31-46cd-bef5-f3de41168e55","content":"No `SettingsPage.xaml` exists in this directory. Since there's no file to modify, here's how to convert it:\n\n## Add `x:DataType` for Compiled Bindings\n\nAdd the `x:DataType` attribute to your `ContentPage`, pointing to your ViewModel's full type:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             xmlns:vm=\"clr-namespace:YourApp.ViewModels\"\n             x:Class=\"YourApp.Views.SettingsPage\"\n             x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\">\n\n    <StackLayout Padding=\"20\">\n        <Entry Text=\"{Binding Theme}\" />\n        <Switch IsToggled=\"{Binding NotificationsEnabled}\" />\n        <Slider Value=\"{Binding FontSize}\" Minimum=\"8\" Maximum=\"36\" />\n    </StackLayout>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe key change is `x:DataType=\"vm:SettingsViewModel\"` — this tells the XAML compiler the expected type, enabling compile-time resolution of `{Binding}` expressions.\n\n## Catching Binding Errors at Build Time\n\nOnce `x:DataType` is set, mistyped or missing properties (e.g., `{Binding Themee}`) produce **compiler errors** instead of silent runtime failures.\n\nTo ensure this is strict, add to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Treat binding failures as build errors (enabled by default with x:DataType) -->\n  <MauiXamlCBindingFailureAsWarning>false</MauiXamlCBindingFailureAsWarning>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nWith this setup, `dotnet build` will fail if any binding path doesn't resolve against the declared `x:DataType`. If you need to opt out for a specific binding (e.g., a dynamically-set context), use `x:DataType=\"\"` locally to disable compiled bindings on that element.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"238dcb96-f569-42f5-b61a-2187c9496c33","outputTokens":502,"requestId":"0813:187D22:9F986C:B91645:69F2A7B6"},"id":"aaa9a32d-6f48-44bf